GateDocument.TextWithNodes: CALL FOR PAPERS You are kindly invited to submit position papers for a Workshop Cross- Organisational Workflow Management and Co-ordination San Francisco , February 22 1999 as a part of the conference WACC '99 Objective and Scope : The objective of the workshop is to provide a forum to discuss workflow management and work co-ordination in situations in which processes span several independent organisations . The Internet provides a ubiquitous means of communication , which could be exploited in conjunction with Workflow Management Systems ( WfMS ) to provide cross-organisational collaboration . WfMS and collaboration tools are now widely used within organisations , but currently available systems are not well suited for cross-organisational collaboration . Various related problems have to be addressed before such systems will be able to operate successfully across organisational boundaries : - Technical interoperability ; definition of basic data types , communication protocols , and addressing schemes of participating systems . - Common terminology on the business and contents level , e . g . for orders , receipts , common objects , etc . - Common language for process models and other co-ordination schemas . - Privacy and restriction of access to organisation-internal systems to the needed and desired extent . - Mechanisms for querying and management of inter-organisational process status and history - Inter-organisational management of shared processes Some of these issues are currently being addressed by standardisation efforts such as the Workflow Management Coalition 's Interface 4 , Swap or OMG . There are several efforts on common process and co-ordination languages , and some common terminology problems are solved by standardisation efforts such as EDI / EDIFACT . However , no current approach seems to provide the complete solution . The purpose of this workshop therefore is - to get an overview of ongoing projects and upcoming products , - to compile requirements for such systems , - to learn about first successful deployments , - to identify research issues in cross-enterprise collaboration , - to start building a research community for inter-organisational workflow management and co-ordination . Intended Participants : - People from academia and industry involved in researching and developing systems for cross-organisational workflow management and collaboration . - Participants preparing , conducting and studying the deployment of such systems in their respective organisations . Submission of Position Papers : Potential participants are required to submit a position paper outlining : - results or work in progress - visionary ideas with a rationale for realisation - experience reports Topics of interest include but are not limited to - Access Control Approaches and Systems - Architectures - Cross-enterprise transaction management - Exception and Failure Management - EDI and WfM / Collaborative Systems - Interoperability - Management of cross-organisational workflow / collaborative relationships - Modelling Approaches - Modelling Languages - Organisational and Legal Aspects Position papers must not exceed 2500 words . Please submit through e-mail in either HTML , PostScript or PDF format to Heiko Ludwig IBM Zurich Research Laboratory hlu @ ylnp . jo . fg Depending on the result of the workshop we aim to publish a summary of the results of the workshop in a journal . All accepted papers will be part of a publicly available report . Papers of the main conference can also be submitted as a position paper if related to the subject of cross-organisational workflow management . However , they will not be part of the publicly available report , if accepted at the main conference . Important Dates : Deadline for submissions : Dec 14 1998 Notification of acceptance : Jan 15 1999 Workshop : Feb 22 1999 Form of the Workshop : The workshop aims to provide an interactive forum for discussion . To enable discussion early on , accepted position papers will be made available to the participants over the Web several weeks before the workshop . There will be three kinds of sessions : - A paper session , in which the two or three most interesting approaches or case studies will be presented ( about 30 - 45 min each ) . If possible , the papers can also be presented in the form of an interactive demo . - Position sessions will present the remaining position papers in a short form ( ~ 15 - 20 min ) and provide time for discussion . - A summarising session at the end will discuss , list and structure the requirements that will have been collected during the day and compare the approaches presented with these requirements . The summary created in this session will be the major outcome of the day . The exact time allocation for the different kinds of sessions will depend on the submissions received . Max .
